Energy Capacity and Generation Gap in Indonesia¶

Ethan Chien, Amitesh Gargapati, Emna Sellami, Sandya Wijaya

Abstract¶

Indonesia is a diverse archipelago at the crossroads of the Pacific and Indian oceans and a key player in Southeast Asia's economic landscape. With the constant surge in population and economic activities, there is a demand for a keen assessment of energy needs -- specifically, the efficiency of energy generation.

This study's objective is to forecast electricity generation, energy capacity, and the alignment between them across Indonesian provinces. To do so, we use regression models -- Linear Regression, Ridge Regression, LSTM, and ARIMAX -- to predict energy generation & maximum capacity in 2024, then classification models -- KNN, Random Forest, and Decision Trees -- to predict whether energy is efficient in 2024. Our best regression model was Ridge Regression (RMSE of ~2000) and our best classification model was Random Forest (accuracy of ~70%). Backed by research, we defined energy generation to be 'not efficient' if it reaches 33% or below maximum capacity, 'efficient' if its between 33% and 60% efficient, and "very efficient if above 60%.

While our Ridge Regression model predicted 30/34 provinces to have efficient energy capacity (above 33%), our Random Forest classification model predicted only 15/34. On average, the predicted 2024 ratio of energy generation to capacity is 0.45 -- meaning we predict that in 2024, energy generation will perform at 45% of the maximum capacity. This is considered efficient: our prediction states that Indonesia as a country will have efficient energy generation in 2024.

Our project is not only able to show which countries are likely to be energy production efficient in 2024, but also show how these results will differ based on which prediction method they choose. These insights will guide resource allocation in policy formulation and infrastructure development to meet the escalating energy demands in Indonesia.

Project Background¶

Indonesia is a newly industrialized country between the Pacific and Indian oceans, consisting of more than 1500 islands, and one of the largest markets in Southeast Asia. As the population and economy continue to grow, that means there will be a constant and increasing demand of electricity throughout the country. While it might make sense to build more energy power plants, it is also important to look into the efficiency of the current plants to determine if and where improvements can be made.

Although Indonesia has the most developed economy in Southeast Asia, they still have transmission and distribution issues, especially in rural areas, which are further exacerbated by natural events such as earthquakes. Knowing how much energy will be generated in a province can help the government-subsidized national electricity provider PLN plan ahead. Further, knowing which provinces have untapped energy capacity can help identify where production can be increased without adding more plants.

Additionally, Indonesia has a lot of untapped natural resources. Developing infrastructure for solar, wind, and hydro sources can help the country scale up energy production.

Project Objective¶

The main objective is to train and evaluate different models to predict electricity generation and capacity in Indonesian provinces using socioeconomic, demographic, and environmental features from 3 years prior.

To answer this question, we will break it up into three prediction questions. Firstly, we will use a given province's features (as listed above) to predict its electricity generation. The second question will be using those same factors to predict provinces' energy capacities. The last question will be a classification model: We will generate a new target variable that will split up the efficiency rates into 3 classes: 0 if efficiency is less than 0.33, 1 if efficiency is 0.33 (inclusive) and 0.6 (non-inclusive), and 2 if efficiency is 0.6 or higher. Then, we will make a classification model to predict this target variable.

After the completion of these three questions, we will divide the predicted energy generation by the predicted capacity for each province in each predicted year. We then apply our classification function to each datapoint, assigning 0s, 1s and 2s as we did in our classification model. This will allow us to directly compare the efficiency class of each province in each year based on if we performed the classification before or after modelling.

Adequate energy efficiency is a crucial component necessary to support a growing population and economy. If we can use socioeconomic, demographic, geographical, and other features to predict the energy capabilites of the future, that could help give Indonesian officials and idea of how much they need to scale up energy production.

As a result, our motivation behind our objectives is, as Indonesia currently undergoes rapid economic growth and a surge in population, the demand for electricity is increasing. We aim to address this pressing need by not only advocating for the construction of new energy power plants but also critically examining the efficiency of existing infrastructure. By conducting a detailed analysis of current power plants, we aim to identify areas for improvement to meet the country's growing energy demands sustainably.

Input Data Description¶

All of the datasets we used in this project come from the BPS website, linked here: https://www.bps.go.id/id. BPS is a government agency in Indonesia that is responsible for performing and conducting statistical surveys. Because BPS is a government-run operation, they have a non-commercial goal, which is to provide data so people can track the progress of their advancement as a country. This adds to the ethos and credibility of the data.

In terms of the data on the website, we specifically looked for and used data that has granularity of both the year and the province. There are many datasets on the BPS website, but many of them are country wide data, which wasn't specific enough for what we wanted to do. We also only looked at data between the years 2011 and 2021. If we want to use socioeconomic factors to predict future electricity generation, we need to make sure our data is recent (the farther back into the past we go, the more likely the socioeconomic features will look more different than the current socioeconomic landscape of Indonesia)

We took socioeconomic, geographical, and demographic csv files from the BPS website and merged them to create our features dataframe X. For our target variables we took the energy generation and capacity csv files and attached them to rows of the feature dataframe from three years in the past so that each independent row had a future target variable. We also had to alter the capacity variable a bit by multiplying it by the number of hours in a year as well as dividing by 1000 to convert it to gigawatts, which was the unit of the energy generation target variable.

Data can be difficult to collect, especially at such a large scale as every Indonesian province; as such, there may be a buffer between when the data was actually collected and when it gets aggregated and made available to the public. The year is 2023, and the earliest data we have for the target variable is is 2021. Since this is a time-series prediction, our features need to be from the past to predict the future. These aspects of the data and modeling are the reasons why our features have to be 3 years prior to the year of the target variable.

Data Cleaning¶

Because our data is from a government agency, one would think that the data is fairly clean. However, this wasn't necessarily the case. There were a few limitations of the data that we had to fix:

  1. On the BPS website, for one topic or subject, the data regarding it was split up into three or four different datasets, each one containing a few years. For example, there were a total of four datasets for just the Energy Generation Dataset (one for 2021, 2018-2020, 2014-2017, and 2011-2013). Also, rather than having a column from provinces, a column for the year, and then the column for the features, it had a column for each year in the dataset. This means that for the dataset that represented 2018 to 2020, there was a column for all three years. This was inconvenient as we wanted each variable in one column rather than three split up columns.
  • Solution: After discussion, we felt that it would be easier to format the data in Google Sheets rather than do many Pandas operations. Therefore, we exported all data into xlsx files and imported them into Google Sheets. Once all the data was there, we just shifted the data around until we got our preferred format, exported that as a csv, and imported it into our python notebook.
  1. Because we are doing a time-series prediction with a three year look back period. Therefore, when we created a dataframe with our feature and target variables, we needed the features to be from three years before whenever the target variable came from.
  • Solution: We have the province data from 2011 to 2021. Due to the three year look back period, the earliest prediction we can make is 2014, and the most recent set of features we can use is from 2018. To accomplish this, once we had all the features and target variables aggregated together, I essentially "shifted up" the target variable three years, and dropped the years 2019-2021. That way, the dataframe is able to look like how I described it. This dataframe would end up being the one we used for most of our modeling, the only time we didn't use it was when we did LSTM's, which we will describe later in this project.
  1. Just like there are in many other dataset, there were some NaN values.
  • Solution: We dealt with missing/NaN data using one of two ways.
    • First, our target variables (energy capacity and generation) didn't have any data from 2016, even though our socioeconomic features did. Therefore, we eliminated predicting 2016 data from our dataset (we still used 2016 features to predict 2019).
    • Second, the 'Population', 'GDP', and 'Land Area' features were missing values in the year 2011 and 2016-2021, respectively. For the 'Population' data, we found the missing values on Wikipedia, and filled in the data accordingly. For 'GDP', we also found it on Wikipedia. However, when looking at where Wikipedia got the information, it sourced back to BPS. For 'Land Area', since the land hasn't changed much in recent years between provinces, we decided to use the most recent
    • Third, there were a few sporadic NaN values. We tried to group similar NaN values together so we could come up with a generalized solution to fill them, but we ultimately decided to drop the NaN values. The idea of using regression to fill in some of the values was considered, but we didn't want to predict something using predicted values, as that would heavily increase our model variance/standard deviation. Additionally, we felt that in terms of observations, it would only be around 20 rows, so it didn't feel too bad dropping the rows with NaNs.

## Helper function to preprocess data from BPS
def preprocess(df, value):
    ## only want years 2011-2012
    # except for 2016
    required_columns = ['Province'] + [str(year) for year in range(2011, 2022) if (str(year) in df.columns) and year != 2016]
    filtered_df = df[required_columns]

    ## make it 1 row = 1 province at 1 year instead of 1 province
    melted_df = pd.melt(filtered_df, id_vars='Province', var_name='Year', value_name=value)

    ## making the datatype easy to work with
    # year object to datetime
    melted_df['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(melted_df['Year'], format='%Y')

    melted_df['Year'] = melted_df['Year'].apply(lambda x: x.year)

    # some rows have - as a value which cannot be converted to float, so turn to nan first
    melted_df[value] = pd.to_numeric(melted_df[value].replace('-', pd.NA), errors='coerce')

    return melted_df

def add_target_to_feature_df(feature_df, target_df, target_name):

    full_df[target_name] = clean_target[target_name]

    # print('num nans in target col: ' + str(clean_target[target_name].isna().sum()))

    return full_df

Forecasting and Prediction Modeling¶

PQ1: Energy Generation [Regression]¶

Models: Linear, Ridge¶

Before implement our modeling, here is a function we made that returns our metrics to test our models after training. so we can easily reuse for all of our models. The metrics present in our function are Mean Squared Error, Mean Absolute Error, Root Mean Squared Error, Mean Absolute Percentage Error.

In [ ]:
def print_metrics(y_true,y_pred):
    # report performance
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    print('MSE: '+str(mse))
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    print('MAE: '+str(mae))
    rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
    print('RMSE: '+str(rmse))
    mape = np.mean(np.abs(y_pred - y_true)/np.abs(y_true))
    print('MAPE: '+str(mape))

Ridge Regression

The next model we tried to model for energy generation is Ridge Regression. To address overfitting on the features, we performed K Fold (3 Fold) cross validation to determine an optimal value of the regularization factor alpha, which turned out to be 10000. We found that 70-30 training/testing split was the best for providing enough data to train the model, and test on a reasonable subset after. The reason we chose a 3 Fold was because as we have such limited amount of data, we wanted to make sure we had enough data for each of the folds and achieve improved results through a balance between bias and variance.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import RidgeCV
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

pq1_df = egen_df.copy().drop(['Province', 'Year'], axis=1).dropna()
X = pq1_df.drop('energy_generated', axis=1)
y = pq1_df['energy_generated']

egen_X_train, egen_X_test, egen_y_train, egen_y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.30, random_state = 42)

# Create RidgeCV model with specified alphas and use KFold cross-validation
alphas = [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000]
kf = KFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
ridge_cv = RidgeCV(cv=kf, alphas=alphas)
ridge_cv.fit(egen_X_train, egen_y_train)

ridge_alpha = ridge_cv.alpha_ # get optimal alpha value
print("optimal alpha:", ridge_alpha)

egen_y_pred = ridge_cv.predict(egen_X_test)

print_metrics(egen_y_test, egen_y_pred)

PQ2: Energy Capacity; Max Generation [Regression]¶

Models: Linear, Ridge, LSTM, ARIMAX¶

To make things easier, let's first define a function that will print metrics for all our regression problems. It will output 4 different error metrics: Mean Squared Error (MSE), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), and Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE). Based on a stakeholder's use case, one may prioritize a model's performance on a specific error metric which leads to different model preferences for each stakeholder.

In [ ]:
def print_metrics(y_true,y_pred):
    # report performance
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    print('MSE: '+str(mse))
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    print('MAE: '+str(mae))
    rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
    print('RMSE: '+str(rmse))
    mape = np.mean(np.abs(y_pred - y_true)/np.abs(y_true))
    print('MAPE: '+str(mape))

In our case, we prioritize RMSE to understand the magnitude of errors irrespective of direction, and MAPE to show accuracy; relative error between predictions and actual values. Now that we know what error metrics we want to prioritize, let's move on to modeling!

Ridge Regression

Now, let's try Ridge regression, a type of regularized linear regression that adds a regularization term -- L2 penalty -- to the traditional linear regression objective function. It has the advantage of reducing the variance of the model by shrinking the coefficients toward zero. A hyperparameter we can tune here is alpha, which defines the strength of the regularization (0 to infinity); In this this case, we used K-Fold (3-Fold) cross validation to find the optimal alpha value. We had the same reasoning for 3 Fold as we had in our Energy Generation Ridge Regression Model. [optimal alpha = 10000]

In [ ]:

Long Short Term Memory (LSTM)

Simpler models such as linear regression and ridge regression are great for interpretability, however, they do not consider sequence dependency -- making them generally unsuitable for predictions across time (and more suited for predictions across space). Recurrent neural networks are designed to handle sequence dependence, and the Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM network) is a type of RNN used in deep learning because very large architectures can be successfully trained. Here is how it works in brief terms:

  • LSTM's gates dynamically learn dependencies across sequences = allowing it to capture complex temporal patterns and long-range dependencies more effectively.
  • LSTMs memory cells preserves and process information over varying input sequences = can handle non-stationary data (data that exhibit trends and thus eligible for time series prediction)
  • LSTM gates control the flow of information = allowing it to capture and update information in the memory cells based on the input and past memory content.

# 4) Now, get x train & y train from the training set
x_train = []
y_train = []

# choose 3 year as the lookback period; 2000 to predict 2003, and so on
for i in range(3, len(train_data['scaled_values'])):
    historical_values = train_data['scaled_values'][i-3:i]
    # additional features to historical data
    additional_features = ['prop_homeowners', 'prop_working', 'prop_school_absentees', 'prop_toilet_access', 'gdp', 'population', 'land_area']
    additional_feature_values = np.empty((len(historical_values), len(additional_features)))
    for idx, feature_name in enumerate(additional_features): 
        # gather values for each of the features for the same lookback period
        feature_values = train_data[feature_name][i-3:i]
        additional_feature_values[:, idx] = feature_values
    # combine historical & additional features
    combined_features = np.column_stack((historical_values, additional_feature_values))
    x_train.append(combined_features)
    # Check if the index exists in 'scaled_values' before appending to y_train
    if i in train_data.index:
        y_train.append(train_data['scaled_values'][i])
    
x_train, y_train = np.array(x_train), np.array(y_train)

# converting it back to 3D array as required by LSTM
x_train = np.reshape(x_train, (x_train.shape[0], x_train.shape[1], x_train.shape[2]))

Our neural network architecture stacked

  • 3 LSTM layers which basically store the information
  • Add dropout layers after each LSTM layer. Dropout layers are a way to prevent overfitting because they act as a valve that closes once in a while, thus controlling the flow of information so the machine stops learning randomly and getting stuck on specific details
  • All the machines compiled knowledge goes through a dense layer with a linear activation function to act as the regression element. Some hyperparameters of a neural network were number of LSTM units (in our case, 50 x 3 layers), dropout rate (0.2 x 3 layers), learning rate (default), batch size (32), number of epochs (50). Our model takes in information in batches of size 32 and does this process 50 times; 50 epochs before spitting out the prediction values.

# Initialize model
lstm = Sequential()
# LSTM layer 1
lstm.add(LSTM(units = 50, return_sequences = True, input_shape = (x_train.shape[1], x_train.shape[2])))
lstm.add(Dropout(0.25)) # dropout layers help prevent overfitting; switches off machine randomly to prevent hyperfixing on specific details 
# LSTM layer 2
lstm.add(LSTM(units = 50, return_sequences = True))
lstm.add(Dropout(0.25))
# LSTM layer 3
lstm.add(LSTM(units = 50))
lstm.add(Dropout(0.25))
# final layer
lstm.add(Dense(units = 1, activation ='linear')) # having activation function linear is suited for regression
lstm.summary()

We see that in general, the LSTM does not perform too well -- the orange predicted line is quite far from the dark blue actual values, and our error metrics RMSE and MAPE are fairly high. This may be due to how LSTM are prone to overfitting, especially on small datasets and/or when the model complexity is high. Regularization techniques like dropout or early stopping are often used to mitigate overfitting, but as seen by our high MSE, they might not always solve this issue. Additionally, LSTM are designed to capture long-term dependencies. Since our the food loss prediction task involves intricate, non-linear, & distant relationships between variables, the model struggles to effectively utilize these dependencies.

ARIMA - Non-exogenous

Let's try another model that is suited for short-term predictions! Doing some simple searching, we noticed that a popular model is ARIMAx, which stands for the following:

  • AR (AutoRegressive): captures the relationship between the current observation and its past values
  • I (Integrated): involves differencing the time series to make it stationary
  • MA (Moving Average): models the relationship between the current observation and a residual error from a moving average model applied to lagged observations
  • X (Exogenous Variables): adds in additional correlated variables to the target goal to tune its predictions

Before we start an ARIMAx model, we must first find autocorrelation using moving average/moving STD test and Adfuller test. There are 2 primary way to determine whether a given time series is stationary.

  1. Rolling Statistics: Plot the rolling mean and rolling standard deviation. The time series is stationary if they remain constant with time (with the naked eye look to see if the lines are straight and parallel to the x-axis).
  2. Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test: The time series is considered stationary if the p-value is low (according to the null hypothesis) and the critical values at 1%, 5%, 10% confidence intervals are as close as possible to the ADF Statistics
In [ ]:
def get_stationarity(time_series):
    rolling_mean = time_series.rolling(window=4).mean()
    rolling_std = time_series.rolling(window=4).std()

    # rolling statistics plot
    original = plt.plot(time_series, color='blue', label='Original')
    mean = plt.plot(rolling_mean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    std = plt.plot(rolling_std, color='black', label='Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    plt.show(block=False)

    # DickeyFuller test:
    result = adfuller(time_series['energy_capacity'])
    print('ADF Statistic: {}'.format(result[0]))
    print('p-value: {}'.format(result[1]))
    print('Critical Values:')
    for key, value in result[4].items():
        print('\t{}: {}'.format(key, value))

PQ3: Optimal Or Not [Classification]¶

Making Multiclass Classification Target Variable¶

Our overarching question is trying to predict whether or not a province's electricity generation, given its socioeconomic factors, is at a certain amount of efficiency. Indonesia's main source of energy is from coal and fossil fuels. After research, we found that most power plants that use similar sources have an efficiency of around 40%, and those that are very efficient peak out at around 60%. Using this information, we determined our threshold of "not efficient" to be below (33.33)%, or 1/3. For the plants that we thought were "adequate efficiency" were between the values 33% and 60%. Lastly, power plants that were above 60% were our final class. To calculate the plants efficiency, we took the province's energy capacity (Mega Watts or MW) and multiplied it by the number of hours (h) in a year to get their maximum possible of energy in Mega Watt hours, or MWh). Then, we needed to convert the MWh to Gigawatt hours, or GWh, which is the unit that Energy Generation is measured in. Once we translated that over, we divided each energy generation value by its corresponding maximum possible energy generated to get their efficiency.

As mentioned above, we split into three classes based on our thresholds. In terms of how we put that into code, if a province's efficiency was below 1/3, it was class 0. If it was above 1/3 and below 0.6, then it was classified as class 1. If its efficiency was above 0.6, then it was placed in class 2. Class 0 had 104 observations, Class 1 had 100 observations, and Class 2 had 28 observations. For these classes, we inherently made the most efficient class the smallest class. In doing so, it seems like being above the threshold can seem like something "exclusive", thus pushing provinces to strive to reach numbers above this threshold. Another point about the classes is that it was intentional of making the classes having an order of 0, 1, and 2. This is because we want there to be ordering in the classification; the power plants that are more efficient can be considered better than those that are not.

After the target classification variable was created, we added it to our dataframe and did a little more cleaning (dropped NaNs and the Indonesia province, as that row was just the sum or average of all the features in Indonesia). Then, we dropped columns that we didn't want to be features (province name, year, energy capactiy and generation), made the X and y variables, and did our train test split. For the split, we chose to do a 0.2 test size. We didn't want to do any larger than that since we already don't have that much data, but we didn't want to do any smaller as we would be losing data on our training. All things considered, we felt that 0.2 test size was the best middle ground we could do.

Models: KNN, Decision Trees, Random Forest¶

In the below cell we prepare X and y (target variable), and split up data into training & testing sets.

K-Nearest Neighbors

The first classification model we made was K-nearest Neighbors, or KNN. The reason behind picking this is that it is fairly simple model, both in it's implementation and its understanding. Therefore, this can give us a baseline to compare our other models with.

As a general rule of thumb, we wanted k to be around the square root of the total number of observations, which in this case would be 15. However, for this multiclass model, the smallest class only had 28 observations, so 15 would be way too large of a k. To figure out a good value for k, we used 10 fold cross validation to find the best value of k, and found that 3 was also the one it chose. We agreed with this choice because for two main reasons. The first one is the one I just mentioned in having a class that was quite small. Secondly, we don't know exactly how many patterns there are in the data, and because the data is fairly trustworthy in that it was collected by the government, the hope is that there isn't too much noise.

For the majority of this classification section, we decided to do cross validation with 10 folds. Most commonly, the number of folds is usually either 10 or 5, so those were the choices we came down to. The reasoning behind opting for 10 is that our dataset is rather small and has a lot of variance.

  • For the first aspect, there are 38 provinces in Indonesia and we only have 7 years of features (from 2011 to 2018, excluding 2016). That leaves us with 266 observations, not to mention that we would end up dropping a few do deal with NaN values.
  • For the second part, each row represents a different province, and each province has a lot of variation in their socioeconomic factors. Because of this large variance, the hope is that by increasing the number of folds in the cross validation that this variance will average out across the folds, giving us a better cv accuracy at the end.

Decision Tree

Our second model we did was a Decision Tree Classifier. The rationale behind using a decision tree classifier is that we wanted the decision tree to ignore outliers. We feel that decision trees are good at not being influenced by outliers in our data. Additionally, decision trees have very easy to interpret when compared to other classification models, such as neural networks. These two reasons are the main motivating factors for using decision trees.

For tuning the hyperparameters, the only parameter we put in the cross validation was max_depth. Same as KNN, we decided to use 10 folds for similar reasons. After running it, CV determined that the best value for max_depth was 9. We used this value in our model, but also understand that a max_depth of 9 is pretty high, making the model prone to overfitting. Another limitation is that because our class 2 is so small, decision trees sometimes might favor the dominant class(es). Class 0 and 1 have significantly more observations in them, so that may mean class 2 will be even more rare in the predictions.

Random Forest

Of the models we ran, our random forest model was the classification model that had the highest accuracy! And this makes sense, because the ensemble method is the average of many decision trees, so it stands to reason that the random forest will perform better than the decision tree. When we did the k-fold cross validation for decision trees, we thought to hypertune the max_depth and n_estimator parameters. For decision trees, max_depth is usually hypertuned to minimize overfitting the training data. But when we thought about this in regards to random forests, random forest already combat overfitting by averaging over many decision trees and randomizing which features are included in each tree. Because of this, we decided to not specify max_depth for random forests.

As for the n_estimators parameter, we decided to use sklearn's RandomizedSearchCV. We used RandomizedSearchCV instead of GridSearchCV because the former allows us to pass in a distribution of values rather than specific values. Since there are a large range of possible n_estimator values, using this cross validation strategy instead of the other ones was beneifical for us. Like the other classification models above, we decided to use 10 fold cross validation.

Resource Allocation¶

Although Indonesia has the most developed economy in Southeast Asia, they still have transmission and distribution issues, especially in rural areas, which are further exacerbated by natural events such as earthquakes. Knowing how much energy will be generated in a province can help the government subsidized electricity provider PLN plan ahead.

Forecasts of future energy generation could be looked at along with population trends to determine if each province will be generate enough in a given year to keep up with the needs of its population? If so, look at provinces infrastructure and try to emulate nationally. If not, allocate funds to improve infrastructure and increase energy importation.

Indonesia has not lived up to its full potential in terms of renewable energy development. Using predictions of future gaps between energy capacity and generation, Indonesian lobbyists and activists could know which provinces to pour more resources and effort into in terms of campaigning for the government to develop more solar, wind, geothermal, and hydropower energy infrastructure. A grid that has more capacity than generation might need to see other sources of energy for that capacity to be met.

Limitations¶

  • A few unreliable results => The MAPE metric seemed to have different range for various models, it was >1 in linear & ridge, when it should be between 0-1 like in LSTM & ARIMAX. Such discrepancy will affect our assessment of which models performed better and affect model choice. Additionally, one of the predicted ratios of energy generation:capacity seem unreliable, specifically how Papua has a negative predicted ratio of ~-1.7 when all ratios should be positive values; generation should not be negative.
  • Dataset is not large enough => We are only using 2011-2015, 2017-2021 data for our project -- that is a total of 10 years. Especially when a model only takes in data per province, this means our input data only has 10 rows. Such a small dataset is not representative, and we are intruiged to see how results change with a larger dataset, such as hundreds of years back & also including more extensive features specifically in the physical realm (temperature, etc.).
  • Initial missing values => Since all our features & target variables came from different datasets, they were quite inconsistent with the years. While we were able to impute some data, there are still some discrepancies. We believe that with more data available at more consistent times across variables, every model would have higher performance, and our chosen model would likely differ. For example, ARIMAX showed great promise but since it only took in <10 rows of data, we deemed this model unreliable and settled on Ridge Regression instead despite it being unsuitable for handling the sequence dependence of time series data -- with more data, we expect ARIMAX has potential winning performance.
